In this article, President Barack Obama declares September 2014 as National Ovarian Cancer Awareness Month. He highlights the seriousness of ovarian cancer, stating that it is the most deadly of all female reproductive system cancers. He mentions that this year, 22,000 Americans will be diagnosed with ovarian cancer and more than 14,000 will die from it. The President emphasizes the importance of early detection and raises awareness about the difficulty of detecting ovarian cancer early. He encourages all women to pay attention to their bodies and seek medical attention if they experience unexplained changes such as abdominal pain, pressure, and swelling. The President also mentions the Affordable Care Act, which expands access to healthcare for women and prohibits insurance companies from denying coverage due to pre-existing conditions. He highlights the importance of regular health checkups and the critical research being done to improve early detection and care for ovarian cancer. The President calls upon citizens, government agencies, organizations, healthcare providers, and research institutions to raise awareness about ovarian cancer and continue supporting efforts to combat the disease.